<DOC><DOCNO> AP900706-0247 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-90 2057EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-MagazinesSold     07-06 0255</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Magazines Sold,0265</SECOND><HEAD>Former Sun-Times Publisher Buys 2 Reader-Written Magazines</HEAD><DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Page Group Publishing Inc. haspurchased a pair of reader-written magazines in Beverly Hills andBrentwood.   Page Group, headed by former Chicago Sun-Times publisher RobertE. Page, bought the Glendale News Press and the Costa Mesa-basedOrange Coast Daily Pilot last year.   Page said Thursday he paid between $1 million and $2 million forthe Brentwood Bla-Bla and Beverly Hills, the Magazine, which aredistributed free.   The Beverly Hills publication has a circulation of 65,000, theWest Los Angeles magazine 75,000, according to their founder andformer majority owner, Michael Lobkowicz.   The magazines feature prose, artwork, poetry and reviewssubmitted by readers, published virtually unedited. No payment isgiven to the authors, who have included such well-known localresidents as Zsa Zsa Gabor, Kenny Rogers and Norman Lear.   Page said he hoped to build a regional media company when he ledan investor group that purchased the Glendale and Costa Mesa paperslast year.   He purchased the magazines from Metropolitan Media Inc. in WestLos Angeles. Lobkowicz will stay on as their publisher and thereare no plans to change the editorial content or the staff of 26people, Page said.   The Costa Mesa-based Page Group also owns weekly newspapers inHuntington Beach, Burbank and La Canada Flintridge.   Lobkowicz said a third magazine that he launched recently,titled the Prince and the Bear, will be reformulated to appear as areader-written insert in Thursday editions of the Daily Pilot.</TEXT></DOC>